f=Governance/precedent/custom/consistency-check/SKILL.md · in=consistency-check contradiction detector: before proposed board ruling finalized, tests proposal against precedent set, they conflict forces explicit choice **distinguish** (the cases differ materially, rulings stand) **overrule** (the old rule wrong wrong; new ruling replaces it, justification logged). What never allows third option organization defaults to: ruling inconsistently noticing. · p=Inconsistent rulings governance loses authority facts got APPROVE March REJECT July stated reason, rulings become arguments rather precedents, future proposer relitigates. skill makes consistency default *deliberate change* alternative: precedent absolutely overruled, overruling visible, justified act, never drift. · wu=Triggers: "consistent past," "precedent conflict," "have ruled differently before," automatically board *proposed* ruling hand ruling-log surfaced similar precedents. · st:/ Protocol=`Take the proposed ruling + the surfaced precedent set \· -> For each precedent: would its ratio, applied to this case, produce the same ruling? \· -> Same → consistent, note and proceed \· -> Different → CONFLICT: present both to board \· -> DISTINGUISH (name the material difference — cases differ, both stand)` · h3:Phase Frame Comparison=surfaced precedent, use `case-law-method`'s extraction (ratio material facts) ask one question: *if ratio applied case, produce proposed ruling?* Yes consistent. conflict. · h3:Phase Present Conflicts, Sides=conflict, present board: prior ruling (ID, case, ratio, rationale) proposed ruling side side, specific point contradiction stated one sentence. recommendation smuggled point make choice unavoidable, make it. · h3:Phase Force Choice=**DISTINGUISH** board names material factual difference (per case-law-method's materiality bar: changed prior outcome). rulings stand; distinction recorded new ruling's record two cases stop looking contradictory future readers., **OVERRULE** cases genuinely match board (with operator, anything operator originally decided) rules differently anyway. Mandatory justification: *what changed* new information, changed circumstances, honest admission prior ratio wrong. overruled ruling stays log (append-only), marked overruled-by new ruling's ID; new ruling records what overruled why. · h3:Phase Force Choice=proposed ruling neither distinguish justify overrule follow precedent that's discipline working intended. · h3:Phase 4 — Log=conflict, choice, justification ruling record (ruling-log schema). Overrules additionally get flagged output operator sees rule change explicitly changed rule governance event, footnote. · of=`## Consistency Check: [proposed ruling, one line] \·  \· **Precedents compared:** [N; IDs] \·  \· ### Consistent` · pr=**Consistency default; change deliberate.** Precedent bends through named distinctions justified overrules never through drift., **Overrules never silent.** Mandatory justification, records cross-marked, operator notified., **The overruled ruling stays.** Append-only history: future readers see rule, change, reason log's whole value., **No manufactured distinctions.** Escaping inconvenient precedent immaterial differences drift wearing costume; materiality bar case-law-method's (would changed prior outcome?)., **Present, don't decide.** skill makes conflict unavoidable; board operator make call. · f=precedents point nothing check; note proposed ruling sets fresh precedent., Precedents conflict *with other* (latent inconsistency already log) surface finding; board resolves which line survives, distinguish-or-overrule protocol applied retrospectively., prior ruling operator overrule board operator's rule precedent, board's original recommendation; conflicts escalate operator directly. · b:with Other precedent Skills=`ruling-log` supplies precedent set; `case-law-method` supplies ratio/materiality machinery; skill owns conflict protocol. sequence live review: log surfaces method extracts skill tests *proposed* ruling., Boundary board: runs last step before board finalizes any ruling precedents point. Board overrule precedent; cannot skip justification.